==English==

===Etymology===
Attested in the 13th Century {{C.E.}}; from [[clergie]], from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|clergié||learned men|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|clericatus||lang=la}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|sc=polytonic|clericus||one ordained for religious services|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|κληρικός|sc=polytonic|tr=klērikos||of the clergy|lang=grc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈklɜːrdʒi/}}
* {{audio|en-us-clergy.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɜː(r)dʒi}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|clerg|ies}}

# Body of persons, such as [[minister]]s, [[priest]]s and [[rabbi]]s, who are trained and ordained for [[religious]] service.

